<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910607-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910607-0022.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Company Slates   Nuclear-Fuel Venture   With Soviet Agency</HL><DATE>06/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8D</SO><IN>NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>NUCLEAR POWER, ENERGY (NUK)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>COLORADO (CO)EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SWITZERLAND (SZ)SOVIET UNION (UR)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   DENVER -- A company controlled by Denver businessman OrenL. Benton has entered into a joint venture with a Soviettrade association to market Soviet nuclear-fuel products andservices to utilities in the U.S. and the Far East.   Concord , a holding company that Mr. Benton owns, said itreached the agreement with Techsnabexport, a foreign tradeassociation of the Soviet Ministry of Atomic Energy andIndustry. The joint venture will be called Global NuclearServices andamp; Supply Inc., and expects to open offices inMoscow, Zurich and Washington, D.C., this year.</LP><TEXT>   Earl Hoellen, president and chief operating officer,declined to say how much Concord has invested in the venture,but said the amount is &quot;significant.&quot; He said the companyexpects the joint venture to record more than $100 million inannual revenue by 1995.   Concord said Techsnabexport has exclusive rights to marketcertain of the ministry's products, including uranium anduranium-enrichment services. The company said that the SovietUnion has abundant uranium deposits and that the ventureshould be competitive world-wide as a low-cost uraniumproducer. It also said the venture could lead to substantialinvestments by the Soviets in Western industrial and consumergoods.   In addition to interests in mining, banking and otherindustries, Concord owns Nuexco, a large nuclear-fuel tradingorganization.</TEXT></DOC>